{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Members of this family closely resemble cysteine synthase but contain an additional C-terminal CBS domain. Cysteine synthase (O-acetylserine (thiol)-lyase) is the enzyme responsible for the formation of cysteine from O-acetyl-serine and hydrogen sulphide with the concomitant release of acetic acid -the function of many of these enzymes is unproven.</p>\n\n<p>This entry includes human CBS protein, which is a hydro-lyase catalysing the first step of the transsulfuration pathway, where the hydroxyl group of L-serine is displaced by L-homocysteine in a beta-replacement reaction to form L-cystathionine, the precursor of L-cysteine. This catabolic route allows the elimination of L-methionine and the toxic metabolite L-homocysteine [[cite:PUB00077989], [cite:PUB00077990], [cite:PUB00077991]]. Mutations in the CBS gene cause cystathionine beta-synthase deficiency (CBSD), an enzymatic deficiency resulting in altered sulfur metabolism and homocystinuria [[cite:PUB00077992], [cite:PUB00077990]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "6c2z", "name" "Crystal Structures of Cystathionine beta-Synthase from Saccharomyces cerevisiae: the Structure of the PLP-Aminoacrylate Intermediate"}, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR036052", "name" "Tryptophan synthase beta chain-like, PALP domain superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"ncbifam" {"TIGR01137" "cystathionine beta-synthase"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Cystathionine beta-synthase", "short" "Cysta_beta_synth"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 34, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 3234, "taxa" 10785, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 8637, "sets" 0, "proteins" 8632, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 5903}, "pathways" 8}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {"gp" {"displayName" "Genome Properties", "description" "